      "[Al+3].[Cl-].[Cl-].[Cl-]"
    ],
    "rationale": "The Fries rearrangement of phenyl acetate to 2-hydroxyacetophenone is a classic, simple, and unambiguous textbook example of this reaction family. It clearly demonstrates the core transformation: the migration of an acyl group from a phenolic oxygen to an ortho position on the aromatic ring, catalyzed by a Lewis acid (AlCl3). The reactants and products are small, acyclic where possible (acyl group), and lack complex functional groups, making it an ideal canonical seed.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "This example uses the simplest possible aromatic system (phenyl) and acyl group (acetyl) to avoid overlap with more complex aromatic substitution or rearrangement reactions. It avoids motifs like polycyclic arenes, complex substituents, or other reactive functional groups that could trigger false positives for unrelated named reactions. The focus is purely on the acyl group migration characteristic of the Fries rearrangement."
  }
}
